occurrences.line_text: That she is fairer, then our fairest Dame,
A fairer wight did neuer Sunne behold,
Or fairer then her selfe, if ought algate
Might fairer be. And then she forth her brought
As white seemes fairer, macht with blacke attone;
Cannot two fairer Cities find this day,
Much fairer, then the former, was that roome,
Did fall in loue: yet this much fairer shined,
But that strange Knight, the fairer loue to gaine,
Of Faerie knights and fairest Tanaquill,
To be the fairest wight, that liued yit;
For fairest Vnaes sake, of whom I sing,
Exceeding shone, like Phoebus fairest childe,
Where he vnwares the fairest Vna found,
O fairest virgin, full of heauenly light,
Where when that fairest Vna she beheld,
In which that fairest Faerie Queene doth dwell,
The fairest Citie was, that might be seene;
The fairest peece, that eye beholden can:
The fairest Vn' his onely daughter deare,
And thou, O fairest Princesse vnder sky,
Doth beare the fairest flowre in honorable seed.
To whom he thus: ï¿½ fairest vnder skie,
The fairest wight that wonneth vnder skye,
Faire Helena, the fairest liuing wight;
He dying left the fairest Tanaquill,
And eke the fairest Alma met him there
And of the fairest late, now made the fowlest place.
That fairest vertue, farre aboue the rest;
His Cynthia, his heauens fairest light?
Ne let his fairest Cynthia refuse,
Most goodly meede, the fairest Dame aliue:
That she is fairer, then our fairest Dame,
But fairest knight aliue, when armed was her brest.
Abroad thy fresh youthes fairest flowre, but lose
But fairest fortune to the Prince befell,
Is, that she is the fairest wight aliue, I trow.
Affrighted had the fairest Florimell,
Of woman kind it fairest flowre doth spire,
The fairest creature, that he euer saw,
The fairest wight on ground, and most of men esteemed.
Well weened he, that fairest Florimell
The fairest woman wight, that euer eye did see.
From Lacedï¿½mon fetcht the fairest Dame,
Ah fairest Lady knight, (said Paridell)
Early before the heauens fairest light
That fairest Amoret was his by right,
Shall to that fairest Ladie be prefard.
That fairest is and from her faith will neuer swerue.
The hearts of some, that fairest her did weene;
By view of all the fairest to him brought,
She seem'd to passe: so forged things do fairest shew.
The which from him his fairest loue did beare.
Or loue of fairest Ladie could constraine.
That she mote match the fairest of her daies,
Excludes from fairest hope, withouten further triall.
Fairest Pherusa, Phao lilly white,
But chiefely of the fairest Florimell,
And fairly quite him of th'imputed blame,
And fairly couching his steele-headed speare,
They marched fairly forth, of nought ydred,
Add faith vnto your force, and be not faint:
Fly to your faith for succour and sure ayde:
That was the flowre of faith and chastity;
His almes for want of faith he doth accuse;
Lo his Fidessa to thy secret faith I flye.
And quickning faith, that earst was woxen weake,
That flowre of faith and beautie excellent.
And learnd her discipline of faith and veritie.
Despaire breedes not (quoth he) where faith is staid.
No faith so fast (quoth she) but flesh does paire.
All they for want of faith, or guilt of sin,
Whose wondrous faith, exceeding earthly race,
Thou falsed hast thy faith with periurie,
For by the faith, which I to armes haue plight,
And eke the faith, which she to me did bynd;
Firme is thy faith, whom daunger neuer fro me drew.
His falsed faith, and loue too lightly flit,
And we your liege men faith vnto you plight.
And to faire semblaunce doth light faith annexe;
Some of sworne friends, that did their faith forgoe;
Tho each to other did his faith engage,
That fairest is and from her faith will neuer swerue.
The sacred pledge, which in his faith was left,
With breach of faith and loyaltie vnsound,
For which his faith with her he fast engaged,
Is this the faith, she said, and said no more,
To whom his faith he firmely ment to hold,
The pledge of faith, her hand engaged held,
To cure her sonne, as he his faith had lent:
Faith may be giuen, it is by them told,
Now sure (said he) and by the faith that I
Her to obay, sith he his faith had plight,
For breach of faith to her, which he had firmely plight.
Me to deceiue of faith vnto me plight,
And swearing faith to either on his blade,
And kept from complishing the faith, which I did owe.
But sure to me her faith she first did plight,
With so foule blame, as breach of faith once plight,
But dearer then the[m] both, your faith once plighted hold.
No faith so firme, no trust can be so strong,
Faith to his knight, and truth to Ladies all,
Sir Calidore his faith thereto did plight,
Regarding more his faith, which he did plight,
Fierce warres and faithfull loues shall moralize my song.
Right faithfull true he was in deede and word,
Forthwith he runnes with feigned faithfull hast
Was neuer Prince so faithfull and so faire,
Yet she most faithfull Ladie all this while
Of her chast person, and a faithfull mate
My faithfull seruice, that by land and seas
Her faithfull gard remou'd, her hope dismaid,
guides the faithfull knight,
The faithfull knight in equall field
Plaine, faithfull, true, and enimy of shame,
Her faithfull knight faire Vna brings
The faithfull knight now grew in litle space,
Then God she praysd, and thankt her faithfull knight,
Thus when Sir Guyon with his faithfull guide
Long I her seru'd, and found her faithfull still,
The faithfull light of that faire lampe yblent,
Hath bene thy faithfull aide in hard assay,
The faithfull steele such treason no'uld endure,
By faithfull seruice, and meet amenance,
Fro[m] Guendolene his wife, though alwaies faithfull prou'd.
That faithfull is, and better were to die.
But since thy faithfull zeale lets me not hyde
From thence, him firmely bound with faithfull band,
Hauing him trew and faithfull euer tride,
In faithfull loue, t'abide for euer more,
Like faithfull friends thenceforth to ioyne in one
That mortall foes doe turne to faithfull frends,
And that old aged Dame, his faithfull Squire,
True loue and faithfull friendship, she by her did set.
There did I finde mine onely faithfull frend
But faithfull friendship doth them both suppresse,
Ah my deare dread (said then the faithfull Mayd)
The righteous Knight, that is thy faithfull louer.
And that they should for euer faithfull bee,
He sent to her his basenet, as a faithfull band.
All which accepting, and with faithfull oth
A courteous Knight, and full of faithfull trust:
And as it mote a faithfull friend behoue,
That I the same should faithfully fulfill,
And deadly foes so faithfully affrended,
And faithfully did serue both day and night,
A faithlesse Sarazin all arm'd to point,
subdewes his faithlesse foe,
To bath in bloud of faithlesse enemy;
It was a faithlesse Squire, that was the sourse
And holy Church with faithlesse hands deface,
And bid his faithlesse chickens ouerronne
And knighthood fowle defaced by a faithlesse knight.
And for a Ladie gainst a faithlesse knight;
Faithlesse Duessa, and false Paridell,
With faithlesse Blandamour and Paridell,
Made him become most faithlesse and vnsound:
Attacht that faitor false, and bound him strait:
A false infamous faitour late befell
False faitour Scudamour, that hast by slight
Lo faitour there thy meede vnto thee take,
The Lady when she saw her champion fall,
Let fall her eyen, as shamefast to the earth,
In which his harder fortune was to fall
Might fall on her, and follow all the way,
And fall away, it mounted was full hie,
To weet what end to straunger knights may fall.
That twise he reeled, readie twise to fall;
Why suffredst thou thy Nephewes deare to fall
The fall of famous children borne of mee,
And he the man that made Sansfoy to fall,
The antique ruines of the Romaines fall:
Which all through that great Princesse pride did fall
The woodborne people fall before her flat,
The wofull Dwarfe, which saw his maisters fall,
Before that shield did fade, and suddeine fall:
Themselues, for feare into his iawes to fall,
The monster mercilesse him made to fall,
Whose fall did neuer foe before behold;
The righteous man, to make him daily fall?
Did fall to ground, and with his heauie sway
Did fall to ground, depriu'd of natiue might;
And in his fall his shield, that couered was,
He downe let fall his arme, and soft withdrew
Whom when his maistresse proud perceiu'd to fall,
Doth roll adowne the rocks, and fall with fearefull drift.
Such was this Gyaunts fall, that seemd to shake
Whose grieuous fall, when false Duessa spide,
Doth soonest fall in disauentrous fight,
Into the which hereafter thou maiest happen fall.
To lead aright, that he should neuer fall
For as the tree does fall, so lyes it euer low.
For that reprochfull fall right fowly he disdaynd.
Since late she saw him fall before his enemy.
With his vneuen wings did fiercely fall
The tree of life, the crime of our first fathers fall.
When gentle Vna saw the second fall
The knight himselfe euen trembled at his fall,
To tell, how he had seene the Dragons fatall fall.
Reioycing at the fall of that great beast,
Hath made sad witnesse of thy fathers fall,
Let one word fall that may your griefe vnfold,
That downe they let their cruell weapons fall,
I giue thee life: therefore prostrated fall,
Sore bruzed with the fall, he slow vprose,
Vnder Sir Guyons puissaunt stroke to fall,
She by creation was, till she did fall;
All which he did, to doe him deadly fall
Or did he fall by treason, or by fight?
The one vpon his couered shield did fall,
Yet sith his fate so cruelly did fall,
That with the noise it shooke, as it would fall:
Such was the end, that to disloyall loue did fall.
Or his dead corse should fall vpon the flore;
A second fall redoubling backe againe.
So soone as he vnto her wombe did fall;
His looser garment to the ground did fall,
That secretly doth vs procure to fall,
Ne suffred storme nor frost on them to fall,
And laughter to her blushing, as did fall:
With the base murmure of the waters fall:
The waters fall with difference discreet,
Yet in his fall so well him selfe he bare,
Great shame and sorrow of that fall he tooke;
And hold them backe, that would in errour fall;
Like sparkes of fire, which fall in sclender flex,
Into his hidden net full easily doth fall.
in loue with him did fall.
But that he it vp-taking ere the fall,
Of secret foes, that him shall make in mischiefe fall.
That it shall make him shake, and shortly learne to fall.
Doth groueling fall, and with his streaming gore
Full myld to her he spake, and oft let fall
Lifteth it vp, that else would lowly fall:
It lets not fall, it lets it not to rest:
Few trickling teares she softly forth let fall,
Besides her golden girdle, which did fall
Downe in a Dongeon deepe he let her fall,
Of wicked Sprights did fall from happy blis;
She low let fall, that flowd from her lanck syde
With his late fall, and fowle indignity,
O lamentable fall of famous towne,
Of that rockes fall, which euer and anon
Threates with huge ruine him to fall vpon,
Her tender waste was wound, adowne gan fall,
Or answere for thy wrong, as shall fall out in fight.
That they at last their wrothfull hands let fall,
And neuer discord did amongst them fall;
One drop of bloud to fall, but did restore
Like as a Lion that by chaunce doth fall
Shall fall the girdle of faire Florimell:
Vpon his heauie eye-lids chaunst to fall,
He sees her face; doth fall in loue,
Saluting him, gan into speach to fall,
Faint friends when they fall out, most cruell fomen bee.
Did fall in loue: yet this much fairer shined,
For feare of perill, which to him mote fall,
That rules the Seas, and makes them rise or fall;
And let their swelling waters low before him fall.
That ill perhaps mote fall to either side.
Through which the rider downe doth fall through ouersight.
All destitute of helpe doth headlong fall,
His foe confused through his sodaine fall,
Should meete, a trap was letten downe to fall
But he was well aware, and leapt before his fall.
Whilest he to gathering of the gold did fall.
For whatsoeuer from one place doth fall,
Weigh but one word which from thy lips doth fall.
And best to him, to whom the best should fall.
That by misfortune in his hand did fall.
Seem'd that for it these Squires at ods did fall,
Whose life did lie in her least eye-lids fall;
Did cast for to allure, into her trap to fall.
The bird, that warned Peter of his fall,
By a false trap was let adowne to fall
That if two met, the one mote needes fall ouer the lidge.
He purposd to proceed, what so be fall,
That for another Canto will more fitly fall.
And in his fall misfortune him mistooke;
A chearefull countenance on them let fall,
But rather let in stead thereof to fall
And yet euen then ruing her wilfull fall,
Vppon the childe, but somewhat short did fall,
That two more of his armes did fall away,
And made him oftentimes in field before me fall.
That in one day they with the coast did fall;
He shund his strokes, where euer they did fall,
To faire Irena, at her feet did fall,
Whose sight to her is greatest crosse, may fall,
How they might make him into mischiefe fall,
That from the battlements she ready seem'd to fall.
Of his late fall, a while he rested still:
Doth fall, whose like hereafter seldome may,
They fall too short of our fraile reckonings,
Where he arriuing with the fall of day,
Here they of force (as fortune now did fall)
That all this land vnto his foe shall fall,
The faire Serena, when she saw him fall
The villaine met him in the middle fall,
As if he neuer had receiued fall;
That with one fall his necke he almost brake,
And to the waters fall tuning their accents fit.
The theeues fall out for Pastorell,
They fall to strokes, the frute of too much talke:
Doe fall together, stryuing each to get
But when the lot to Pastorell did fall,
Looking each houre into deathes mouth to fall,
That backeward he enforced him to fall:
His locks, like faded leaues fallen to grownd,
Trembling through feare, least down he fallen should,
To him was fallen for his happie lot,
Fallen into that Tyrants hand and vsage bad.
And had he not vpon him fallen light,
From all the world after their wofull falles,
At last downe falles, and with her heaped hight
Vnhappie falles that hard necessitie,
The strong through pleasure soonest falles, the weake through smart.
That a large purple streme adown their giambeux falles.
But nought that falles into this direfull deepe,
Loe see soone after, how she fades, and falles away.
It falles me here to write of Chastity,
Well falles it thee that I am not in plight
With dreadfull force falles on some steeple hie;
(As often falles) of sundry things did commen.
To wrong the weaker, oft falles in his owne assault.
Is greatest shame: for oft it falles, that strong
But as it falleth, in the gentlest harts
He falleth nigh to ground, and scarse recouereth flight.
And falleth downe to ground like senselesse thing,
But first it falleth me by course to tell
They saw so rudely falling to the ground,
And falling her before on lowly knee,
As carefull Nourse her child from falling oft does reare.
Where falling flat, great humblesse he did make,
Emongst them ran, and falling them beforne,
Both falling out doe stirre vp strifefull broyle,
And falling heauie on Cambelloes crest,
That scarse he him vpheld from falling in a sound.
And on her knee before him falling lowe,
Where falling downe, his challenge he releast:
That falling on his mother earth he fed:
And falling lowly at his feet, her bowd
Gan stoupe, and falling downe with humble awe,
The which was fall'n into this feeble case,
Falne into mischiefe through intemperaunce,
And languish as the leafe falne from the tree,
Now falne into their fellowship by chance,
Like as an Hynde whose calfe is falne vnwares
Who now was falne into new languishment
Well weening that his foe was falne withall:
Is falne on you, by heauens hard direction,
Now when they saw it falne, they eke him greeted all.
Marres blind Deuotions mart, and fals
Hard is his hap, that first fals in his ieopardie.
The stone-dead quarrey fals so forciblie,
And fals to ground, to seeke for succour theare,
It often fals, (as here it earst befell)
It so befell, as oft it fals in chace,
And in the same are many trap fals pight,
It often fals in course of common life,
That all which I put in, fals out anon;
A fit false dreame, that can delude the sleepers sent.
And with false shewes abuse his fantasy,
And to him playnd, how that false winged boy,
And that false other Spright, on whom he spred
Come see, where your false Lady doth her honour staine.
Where that false couple were full closely ment
And fortune false betraide me to your powre,
Is one Duessa a false sorceresse,
And euer false Duessa seemde as faire as shee.
The false witch did my wrathfull hand with-hold;
The false Duessa, now Fidessa hight,
And false Duessa in her sted had borne,
And false Duessa seeming Lady faire,
For he was false, and fraught with ficklenesse,
Emongst the rest rode that false Lady faire,
No knight, but treachour full of false despight
By this false faytor, who vnworthy ware
Of fortune false, and oddes of armes in field.
Whom false Duessa saues, and for
The false Duessa, Thine the shield, and I, and all.
Which in false griefe hyding his harmefull guile,
The false resemblance of Deceipt, I wist
His father fierce of treason false accused,
The false Duessa leauing noyous Night,
Prouokt with VVrath, and Enuies false surmise,
But that false Pilgrim, which that leasing told,
Great maistresse of her art was that false Dame,
The false Duessa, cloked with Fidessaes name.
He set the false Duessa, for more aw and dread.
The wanton loues of false Fidessa faire,
In which him chaunced false Duessa meete,
No false enchauntment, nor deceiptfull traine
Whose grieuous fall, when false Duessa spide,
Whose false foundation waues haue washt away,
Though false Duessa it to barre
her false sleights doe imploy.
False erraunt knight, infamous, and forswore:
Or false or trew, or liuing or else dead,
Of this false woman, that Fidessa hight,
Most false Duessa, royall richly dight,
Too false and strong for earthly skill or might,
To haue bene wroght by that false sorceresse.
Of this false footman, clokt with simplenesse,
Attacht that faitor false, and bound him strait:
Sith that false Traytour did my honour reaue?
False traytour certes (said the Faerie knight)
Lurckt false Duessa secretly vnseene,
So had false Archimago her disguisd,
A false infamous faitour late befell
Acrasia a false enchaunteresse,
Till I that false Acrasia haue wonne;
By Guyon, and by that false Redcrosse knight,
Where left, he went, and his owne false part playd,
To Philemon, false faytour Philemon
With false delights, and fild with pleasures vaine,
The which emongst the gods false Ate threw;
False Archimage prouokt their courage prowd,
Made it selfe famous through false trechery,
False traitour miscreant, thou broken hast
The whiles false Archimarge and Atin fled apace.
Of false Acrasia, and her wicked wiles,
Had not Androgeus, false to natiue soyle,
Bad counsels, prayses, and false flatteries.
Or aerie spirit vnder false pretence,
Where many Mermayds haunt, making false melodies.
With her false eyes fast fixed in his sight,
Of her false eyes, that at her hart did ayme,
The bird, that knowes not the false fowlers call,
And through her bones the false instilled fire
And read, where I that faytour false may find.
Yet when his loue was false, he with a peaze it brake.
But the false Archer, which that arrow shot
In the meane time through that false Ladies traine,
By false illusion of a guilefull Spright,
And whilome by false Faries stolne away,
Of false Pellite, his purposes to breake,
With double senses, and with false debate,
Fond Proteus, father of false prophecis,
Yet did false Archimage her still pursew,
And his false venim through their veines inspyred;
The wicked engine through false influence,
In speaking, many false belgardes at her let fly.
False loue, why do men say, thou canst not see,
He found, then his false engins fast he plyde,
He wept, and wayld, and false laments belyde,
Thus finely did he his false nets dispred,
Such as false loue doth oft vpon him weare:
Her deedes were forged, and her words false coynd,
Inconstant Chaunge, and false Disloyaltie,
Neither of idle shewes, nor of false charmes aghast.
Through false allurement of that pleasing baite,
Then to be false in loue, profest a virgine wife.
The one of them the false Duessa hight,
Her false Duessa who full well did know,
Fild with false rumors and seditious trouble,
Faithlesse Duessa, and false Paridell,
That whether were more false, full hard it is to tell.
False faitour Scudamour, that hast by slight
So hast thou to thy selfe false honour often wonne.
Ah gentle knight then false Duessa sayd,
So false Duessa, but vile Ate thus;
Fy fy false knight (then false Duessa cryde)
Fy fy false knight (then false Duessa cryde)
False traitour squire, false squire, of falsest knight,
False traitour squire, false squire, of falsest knight,
Yet thou false Squire his fault shalt deare aby,
Blandamour winnes false Florimell,
Through that false witch, and that foule aged dreuill,
And by his false allurements wylie draft
Yet now he was surpriz'd: for that false spright,
So blind is lust, false colours to descry.
His false Duessa, that she might be seene;
That all his gealous feare he false had found,
False crimes and facts, such as they neuer ment,
From his false eyes, into their harts and parts entire.
Those foure were they, from whom false Florimell
False Labyrinthes, fond runners eyes to daze;
Could weenen, whether they were false or trew.
And him doth chyde as false and fraudulent,
Whether old Proteus true or false had sayd,
The right or wrong, the false or else the trew?
He did so first; and then the false he layd
For by no meanes the false will with the truth be wayd.
That his false Ladie, as ye heard afore.
The semblant of this false by his faire beauties Queene.
But the false mayden shortly turn'd againe
In her false hart, his bondage to vnbind;
Sometime least his false foe did him entrap
Ye will not watch? false watches, wellaway,
By a false trap was let adowne to fall
Those two false brethren, on that perillous Bridge,
Thou recreant false traytor, that with lone
These two false Knights, whom there ye lying see,
Can follow out those false footsteps of his,
Laughing on her, his false intent to shade,
That false Duessa, which had wrought great care,
Remember) had her counsels false conspyred,
But false Duessa now vntitled Queene,
And faynes to weaue false tales and leasings bad,
